2026-07-20 FINANCIALS (part 3), SIEMENS ENERGY AND A NEW JURISDICTION: ALL SIX CHOKEPOINTS ARE NOW COSTED
(24 of 30 companies). Siemens Energy was the only chokepoint not reachable through 01's data or SEC XBRL,
and Germany was a jurisdiction this repo had no route for. It turned out to be one of the CHEAP ones:
the company publishes English audited statements on its own IR asset host, one search and one PDF, no
translation. That route and the ECB rate API are now in shared/SOURCING-ROUTES.md so the cost is paid once.

🔴 THE TRAP THAT ALMOST TOOK THE WRONG NUMBER, NOW WRITTEN INTO SOURCING-ROUTES. The statements carry four
columns under two SPANNING headers -- "Q4" over the first two, "Fiscal year" over the last two -- so the
columns read FY 2025 | FY 2024 | 2025 | 2024, and the column that SAYS "FY 2025" is the QUARTER. Revenue
in that column is EUR 10,428M. The actual full year is EUR 39,077M, 3.7x larger, and nothing about the
wrong figure looks wrong. The spanning header is a purely VISUAL fact that flattens away in the text
layer, which is the second independent reason this repo renders pages instead of parsing them.

Both of SOURCING-ROUTES' in-filing cross-checks were run and both passed: attributable 1,414 + minority
271 = 1,685 exactly, and 1,414 / EPS 1.63 = 867.5M shares, which is the right order for Siemens Energy.
Worth noting the press release itself pairs "net income of EUR 1,685m" with "EPS of EUR 1.63" in one
sentence, and those two do not go together: 1,685 / 1.63 implies 1,034M shares. The EPS belongs to the
ATTRIBUTABLE figure. A reader who took the company's own summary sentence at face value would have
overstated the bottom line by 19%.

Market cap left EMPTY: the release states no period-end share count, and an EPS denominator is a weighted
average, not a period-end count. Deriving one would be an approximation dressed as a filing figure.

NEXT: the relationships burst, which is what would make 04 Mapped. Schneider Electric (Euronext) and
Foxconn (TWSE) remain uncosted and are NOT chokepoints, so they rank below edges.

2026-07-20 RELATIONSHIPS BURST -- 04 IS MAPPED. 40 sourced edges from 3 parallel Sonnet workers (silicon /
systems+power / clouds+labs), 41 staged, 41/41 verified by refetch, 1 dropped, 1 duplicate collapsed as a
confirmation. 24 of 30 costed, all 6 chokepoints costed, 40 edges.

🔑 ZERO competes-with, out of 40. 02's burst returned 8 of 14 as competes-with and was graded a partial
failure. The fix was to say so in the prompt: name the failure, state that dependencies are what gets
graded, and list competes-with last among the allowed types. The silicon worker found a ready made
competitor list sitting in Nvidia's own 10-K (AMD, Arista, Broadcom, Cisco, HPE, Huawei, Intel, Lumentum,
Marvell) and deliberately left every one of them on the floor. Telling a worker what counts as padding
works better than hoping it self-restrains.

🔑 THE DELIBERATE OVERLAP PAID OFF, IN THE AGREEING DIRECTION. Two workers were pointed independently at
Nvidia's customer concentration note. Both returned the SAME numbers (FY2026: one direct customer 22%,
another 14%) and the same crucial negative: the customers are NOT NAMED, not even as "Customer A".
Neither wrote an edge guessing who they are. Agreement between independent reads is evidence; on the 02
burst the same technique produced a DISAGREEMENT and the document settled it. Either way it earns its cost.

🔴 THE MOST VALUABLE RESULTS WERE ABSENCES, AND THEY ALMOST ALL LIVE IN THE POWER TIER.
  - NOT ONE of Microsoft, Meta, Alphabet or Amazon names Nvidia anywhere in its own 10-K. Checked by
    full text search, not assumed. Everyone knows they buy the GPUs; no filing of theirs says so.
  - Siemens Energy's own 266 page annual report, Schneider's FY2025 release and Eaton's 10-K name NO
    data center counterparty at all. Zero edges for all three. Vertiv is the lone exception, and only
    because its 10-K's "Our Customers" section names Microsoft, AWS, Google Cloud, CoreWeave and Nebius
    outright, which is 5 of the map's 8 sells-equipment-to edges.
  - TSMC's 20-F never names a customer ANYWHERE ("our largest customer", "our ten largest customers"),
    so the CoWoS packaging edge -- the highest value single target on the list -- could not be written.
    No document ties TSMC + CoWoS + a named customer in one place.
  - Astera Labs uses "Customer A" through "Customer G"; Super Micro anonymises its 20% customer;
    Oracle's $638B remaining performance obligations name no counterparty; Alphabet's $64.1B of
    non marketable equity breaks out no holding, so no Alphabet -> Anthropic edge despite the reporting.
  ⇒ THE AI COMPUTE STACK IS WIDELY REPORTED AND THINLY DISCLOSED. A map that only wrote down what
    filings actually say is a genuinely different artifact from the consensus picture, and that gap IS
    the finding. Recorded rather than papered over.

⚠ SIEMENS ENERGY IS FLAGGED AS A CHOKEPOINT ON ZERO EDGES. Flag KEPT: the transformer argument is about
supplier concentration and multi year lead times, not about any one disclosed contract, and an absence of
disclosure is not an absence of dependency. But it is now the weakest evidenced claim on the map, and the
caveat is written into map.json's chokepoint_why so it renders ON THE PAGE rather than hiding in this log.

